00:01:00.870 --> 00:01:03.500
So you might wanna stick around to watch this.

00:01:03.500 --> 00:01:11.040
It's a little embarrassing, but you might
learn something.

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:16.370
Okay guys, so let's get started: I have never
done this before, so I'm not gonna lie, I

00:01:16.370 --> 00:01:17.370
don't really know what I'm doing.

00:01:17.370 --> 00:01:19.370
This is my assistant: I want you all to meet
Pilar.

00:01:19.370 --> 00:01:20.780
Vamonos, you're gonna help.

00:01:20.780 --> 00:01:21.780
You're gonna stay.

00:01:21.780 --> 00:01:25.360
I'm gonna start first by folding the muslin.

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:28.130
So what you should have is something kind
of like this.

00:01:28.130 --> 00:01:31.310
Okay, then you fold this way, just like you
did the other side.

00:01:31.310 --> 00:01:33.470
Kinda like an accordion, like an accordion
file.

00:01:33.470 --> 00:01:38.160
Now once you have your fold -- super easy
-- grab two rubber bands, and then you'll

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:42.710
just wanna take your rubber bands and put
it like that.

00:01:42.710 --> 00:01:44.560
And we're gonna do the other rubber band.

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:49.370
What's cool about muslin is that it will absorb
the material, the dye, really quickly.

00:01:49.370 --> 00:01:52.230
So once you've got your rubber bands in place,
then you're just gonna wanna submerge your

00:01:52.230 --> 00:01:54.140
fabric in water.

00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:58.350
Now once you've wet your fabric, now it's
time for the fun stuff: We get to color.

00:01:58.350 --> 00:02:02.490
These tubes are great because it's really
easy to apply the color.

00:02:02.490 --> 00:02:06.290
And don't be precious about it, I mean, this
is not, you do not have to be perfect.

00:02:06.290 --> 00:02:12.510
Okay, now once you have this, you're just
gonna wanna let it sit for about 10 minutes.

00:02:12.510 --> 00:02:18.820
So once the dyes have had time to set, then
just go ahead and take off the rubber bands,

00:02:18.820 --> 00:02:23.580
and then we're gonna go ahead and place the
tie-dyed fabric into cold water.

00:02:23.580 --> 00:02:25.810
And see, guys, this is when you really want
gloves.

00:02:25.810 --> 00:02:26.860
I don't know what I was thinking.

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:30.250
I told you I didn't know what I was doing.

00:02:30.250 --> 00:02:34.890
Now once you've wrung out all the water, then
you can kinda shake it out and start to see

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:35.890
the design.

00:02:35.890 --> 00:02:40.430
Now the color is really saturated when the
fabric's still wet, but I already like it.

00:02:40.430 --> 00:02:42.850
I really like the way this turned out so far.

00:02:42.850 --> 00:02:45.630
I know that once it drys, it's gonna get a
little softer, the color.

00:02:45.630 --> 00:02:47.620
And I like the muted hues.

00:02:47.620 --> 00:02:52.570
But if at home, you want something that's
more bold or makes a bigger statement, then

00:02:52.570 --> 00:02:56.410
just saturate the fabric in the color for
a little bit longer, and then you're gonna

00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:59.730
get bolder hues and something that's more
of a statement.

00:02:59.730 --> 00:03:03.470
So we're finished up here, back to you in
the studio, Tracy.

00:03:03.470 --> 00:03:04.470
Thanks, Tracy.

